"# Chapter 7: Squash & Stretch

A rubber ball hits the floor and flattens, then springs back as it rebounds. A flour sack lands heavily, folding over itself before settling. A drop of water splashes wide, then pulls itself together. *Squash* and *stretch* are how we give mass a voice — how we make the rigid look soft, the heavy look earthbound, the light look bouncy. Without them, even a ball with perfect arc and timing reads as a sliding marble.

This chapter drills the **deformation regime** — the axis of the motion 5-tuple that changes *shape* over time, not just position. We'll compose squash and stretch with the weight, timing, and arc ideas from earlier chapters, building toward a bounce that *feels* like a specific material: a medicine ball, a balloon, a water droplet.

[VISUAL: Three bouncing spheres side by side — one remains circular, one squashes deeply on landing and stretches tall on ascent, one squashes only slightly. Caption: \"Same arc, different feels.\"]

## The Atom: A Circle That Deforms

Start with the simplest case: a circle at rest that we can squash and stretch by scaling along its local axes. We won't move it yet — just reshape it.

```scheme
;; A circle squashed flat, then stretched tall
(let ((ball (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 150 :radius 30)))
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-x 1.5)
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-y 0.7))
```

[VISUAL: An ellipse, wider than it is tall, centered in the frame.]

The circle is now an ellipse. `scale-x` and `scale-y` are the deformation knobs. When we vary them over time, we get squash and stretch.

## Squash on Impact, Stretch on Release

A bounce has two moments when deformation is strongest: when the ball *hits* the ground (squash) and when it *leaves* the ground (stretch). Between those moments, the ball tends back toward its rest shape.

```scheme
;; A ball that squashes when it lands, then springs back
(let ((ball (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 50 :radius 24 :vy 0)))
  (entity/gravity-scale! ball 1.0)
  (entity/bounce! ball 0.8)
  (entity/set! ball 'floor 300)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((ground 300)
             (dist-to-floor (- ground (entity/y e)))
             (squash-amount (if (< dist-to-floor 5) 1.5 1.0))
             (stretch-amount (if (< dist-to-floor 5) 0.6 1.0)))
        (entity/set! e 'scale-x squash-amount)
        (entity/set! e 'scale-y stretch-amount)))))))
```

This example checks if the ball is within 5 pixels of the floor — if so, it squashes wide and short. Otherwise, it returns to its rest shape. The effect is abrupt, but it shows the mechanism.

[VISUAL: A bouncing ball that flattens when it touches the ground, then snaps back to round.]

## Easing the Deformation

The snap is too sudden. Real materials don't instantly change shape — they ease into and out of deformation. We can blend the scale values over time, just as we eased position in Chapter 3.

```scheme
;; A ball that eases into squash and out again
(let ((ball (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 50 :radius 24 :vy 0)))
  (entity/gravity-scale! ball 1.0)
  (entity/bounce! ball 0.8)
  (entity/set! ball 'floor 300)
  (entity/set! ball 'squash-target 1.0)
  (entity/set! ball 'stretch-target 1.0)
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-y 1.0)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((ground 300)
             (dist-to-floor (- ground (entity/y e)))
             (target-squash (if (< dist-to-floor 5) 1.5 1.0))
             (target-stretch (if (< dist-to-floor 5) 0.6 1.0))
             (current-x (entity/get e 'scale-x))
             (current-y (entity/get e 'scale-y))
             (ease-rate 0.3)
             (new-x (+ current-x (* (- target-squash current-x) ease-rate)))
             (new-y (+ current-y (* (- target-stretch current-y) ease-rate))))
        (entity/set! e 'scale-x new-x)
        (entity/set! e 'scale-y new-y)))))))
```

Now the deformation eases in and out smoothly. The ball feels more elastic, less mechanical.

[VISUAL: A bouncing ball that smoothly squashes and rounds, with a sense of give.]

## Volume Conservation

Real materials conserve volume when they deform. A squashed ball should widen *because* it's shorter. If we squash in one axis, we should stretch in the other so that the total area remains roughly constant. The product `scale-x * scale-y` should stay near 1.0.

```scheme
;; A ball that conserves volume when squashed
(let ((ball (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 50 :radius 24 :vy 0)))
  (entity/gravity-scale! ball 1.0)
  (entity/bounce! ball 0.8)
  (entity/set! ball 'floor 300)
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-y 1.0)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((ground 300)
             (dist-to-floor (- ground (entity/y e)))
             (target-y (if (< dist-to-floor 5) 0.6 1.0))
             (target-x (/ 1.0 target-y))
             (current-x (entity/get e 'scale-x))
             (current-y (entity/get e 'scale-y))
             (ease-rate 0.3)
             (new-x (+ current-x (* (- target-x current-x) ease-rate)))
             (new-y (+ current-y (* (- target-y current-y) ease-rate))))
        (entity/set! e 'scale-x new-x)
        (entity/set! e 'scale-y new-y)))))))
```

When `scale-y` is 0.6, `scale-x` becomes `1.0 / 0.6 ≈ 1.67`. The ball's area stays constant, and the bounce feels more physically grounded.

[VISUAL: A bouncing ball that widens as it squashes, maintaining a sense of mass.]

## Velocity-Driven Stretch

A ball moving *fast* should stretch in the direction of motion — the faster it moves, the more it stretches. This is the \"motion blur\" of deformation, and it makes speed legible.

```scheme
;; A ball that stretches when moving fast
(let ((ball (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 50 :radius 24 :vy 0)))
  (entity/gravity-scale! ball 1.0)
  (entity/bounce! ball 0.8)
  (entity/set! ball 'floor 300)
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-y 1.0)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((vel-y (entity/vel e))
             (speed (abs (cdr vel-y)))
             (stretch-factor (+ 1.0 (* speed 0.01)))
             (squash-factor (/ 1.0 stretch-factor))
             (current-x (entity/get e 'scale-x))
             (current-y (entity/get e 'scale-y))
             (ease-rate 0.2)
             (new-x (+ current-x (* (- squash-factor current-x) ease-rate)))
             (new-y (+ current-y (* (- stretch-factor current-y) ease-rate))))
        (entity/set! e 'scale-x new-x)
        (entity/set! e 'scale-y new-y)))))))
```

The faster the ball moves vertically, the taller it becomes. When it slows near the apex of its bounce, it rounds back out.

[VISUAL: A bouncing ball that stretches into a tall ellipse during fast upward and downward motion, rounding out at the peak and on the ground.]

## Combining Impact and Velocity

The most convincing bounce combines *both* effects: squash on impact (contact deformation) and stretch during fast motion (velocity-driven deformation). We need to decide which one wins, or blend them.

```scheme
;; A ball that squashes on impact AND stretches when moving fast
(let ((ball (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 50 :radius 24 :vy 0)))
  (entity/gravity-scale! ball 1.0)
  (entity/bounce! ball 0.8)
  (entity/set! ball 'floor 300)
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-y 1.0)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((ground 300)
             (dist-to-floor (- ground (entity/y e)))
             (vel-y (cdr (entity/vel e)))
             (speed (abs vel-y))
             (is-on-ground (< dist-to-floor 5))
             
             ;; Impact deformation
             (impact-y (if is-on-ground 0.6 1.0))
             (impact-x (/ 1.0 impact-y))
             
             ;; Velocity deformation
             (velocity-y (+ 1.0 (* speed 0.008)))
             (velocity-x (/ 1.0 velocity-y))
             
             ;; Blend: impact dominates when on ground, velocity otherwise
             (target-y (if is-on-ground impact-y velocity-y))
             (target-x (if is-on-ground impact-x velocity-x))
             
             (current-x (entity/get e 'scale-x))
             (current-y (entity/get e 'scale-y))
             (ease-rate 0.25)
             (new-x (+ current-x (* (- target-x current-x) ease-rate)))
             (new-y (+ current-y (* (- target-y current-y) ease-rate))))
        (entity/set! e 'scale-x new-x)
        (entity/set! e 'scale-y new-y)))))))
```

Now the ball squashes hard when it hits the floor, then stretches tall as it rockets upward. At the apex, it's nearly round.

[VISUAL: A bouncing ball with pronounced squash on contact and dramatic stretch during ascent and descent.]

## Material: The Heavy Ball

A medicine ball or shot put doesn't squash much — it's rigid and dense. We reduce the deformation magnitude.

```scheme
;; A heavy ball with minimal squash
(let ((ball (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 50 :radius 26 :vy 0)))
  (entity/gravity-scale! ball 1.2)
  (entity/bounce! ball 0.4)
  (entity/set! ball 'floor 300)
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-y 1.0)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((ground 300)
             (dist-to-floor (- ground (entity/y e)))
             (vel-y (cdr (entity/vel e)))
             (speed (abs vel-y))
             (is-on-ground (< dist-to-floor 5))
             
             (impact-y (if is-on-ground 0.92 1.0))
             (impact-x (/ 1.0 impact-y))
             
             (velocity-y (+ 1.0 (* speed 0.002)))
             (velocity-x (/ 1.0 velocity-y))
             
             (target-y (if is-on-ground impact-y velocity-y))
             (target-x (if is-on-ground impact-x velocity-x))
             
             (current-x (entity/get e 'scale-x))
             (current-y (entity/get e 'scale-y))
             (ease-rate 0.3)
             (new-x (+ current-x (* (- target-x current-x) ease-rate)))
             (new-y (+ current-y (* (- target-y current-y) ease-rate))))
        (entity/set! e 'scale-x new-x)
        (entity/set! e 'scale-y new-y)))))))
```

The deformation is subtle — `0.92` instead of `0.6` — and the ball barely bounces. It reads as heavy and solid.

[VISUAL: A ball that bounces low and squashes only slightly, with a dull, thudding feel.]

## Material: The Balloon

A balloon is light and elastic. It squashes deeply on impact, stretches dramatically in flight, and bounces high.

```scheme
;; A balloon with exaggerated squash and stretch
(let ((balloon (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 50 :radius 28 :vy 0)))
  (entity/gravity-scale! balloon 0.4)
  (entity/bounce! balloon 0.9)
  (entity/set! balloon 'floor 300)
  (entity/set! balloon 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! balloon 'scale-y 1.0)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((ground 300)
             (dist-to-floor (- ground (entity/y e)))
             (vel-y (cdr (entity/vel e)))
             (speed (abs vel-y))
             (is-on-ground (< dist-to-floor 5))
             
             (impact-y (if is-on-ground 0.4 1.0))
             (impact-x (/ 1.0 impact-y))
             
             (velocity-y (+ 1.0 (* speed 0.015)))
             (velocity-x (/ 1.0 velocity-y))
             
             (target-y (if is-on-ground impact-y velocity-y))
             (target-x (if is-on-ground impact-x velocity-x))
             
             (current-x (entity/get e 'scale-x))
             (current-y (entity/get e 'scale-y))
             (ease-rate 0.2)
             (new-x (+ current-x (* (- target-x current-x) ease-rate)))
             (new-y (+ current-y (* (- target-y current-y) ease-rate))))
        (entity/set! e 'scale-x new-x)
        (entity/set! e 'scale-y new-y)))))))
```

The balloon squashes almost flat (`0.4`) and stretches significantly during flight. It reads as buoyant and elastic.

[VISUAL: A balloon bouncing high, squashing dramatically on contact, and stretching into a tall shape during flight.]

## Material: The Water Droplet

Water is a special case: it squashes on impact like any soft material, but it also *wobbles* after impact — oscillating between squash and stretch as it settles.

```scheme
;; A water droplet that wobbles after landing
(let ((drop (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 50 :radius 20 :vy 0)))
  (entity/gravity-scale! drop 1.0)
  (entity/bounce! drop 0.6)
  (entity/set! drop 'floor 300)
  (entity/set! drop 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! drop 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! drop 'wobble-phase 0.0)
  (entity/set! drop 'wobble-energy 0.0)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((ground 300)
             (dist-to-floor (- ground (entity/y e)))
             (vel-y (cdr (entity/vel e)))
             (speed (abs vel-y))
             (is-on-ground (< dist-to-floor 5))
             
             (wobble-phase (entity/get e 'wobble-phase))
             (wobble-energy (entity/get e 'wobble-energy))
             
             ;; Add energy on impact
             (new-energy (if is-on-ground
                             (+ wobble-energy (* speed 0.02))
                             (* wobble-energy 0.95)))
             
             ;; Advance wobble phase
             (new-phase (+ wobble-phase (* new-energy 0.3)))
             
             ;; Wobble oscillates scale
             (wobble-offset (* (dsin new-phase) new-energy))
             (target-y (+ 1.0 wobble-offset))
             (target-x (/ 1.0 target-y))
             
             (current-x (entity/get e 'scale-x))
             (current-y (entity/get e 'scale-y))
             (ease-rate 0.25)
             (new-x (+ current-x (* (- target-x current-x) ease-rate)))
             (new-y (+ current-y (* (- target-y current-y) ease-rate))))
        
        (entity/set! e 'wobble-phase new-phase)
        (entity/set! e 'wobble-energy new-energy)
        (entity/set! e 'scale-x new-x)
        (entity/set! e 'scale-y new-y)))))))
```

The droplet oscillates between squashed and stretched after each bounce, with the oscillation gradually damping. It reads as liquid.

[VISUAL: A droplet that wobbles after landing, alternating between wide and tall before settling into a round shape.]

## The Settle: Post-Impact Overshoot

When a soft object lands, it doesn't just squash and return to rest — it *overshoots*, stretching tall before settling. This overshoot gives the bounce a sense of elasticity.

```scheme
;; A ball that overshoots its rest shape after squashing
(let ((ball (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 50 :radius 24 :vy 0)))
  (entity/gravity-scale! ball 1.0)
  (entity/bounce! ball 0.75)
  (entity/set! ball 'floor 300)
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! ball 'deform-vel 0.0)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((ground 300)
             (dist-to-floor (- ground (entity/y e)))
             (vel-y (cdr (entity/vel e)))
             (speed (abs vel-y))
             (is-on-ground (< dist-to-floor 5))
             
             (deform-vel (entity/get e 'deform-vel))
             (current-y (entity/get e 'scale-y))
             
             ;; Push toward squash on impact
             (impact-force (if is-on-ground (* speed -0.02) 0.0))
             
             ;; Spring force toward rest (1.0)
             (spring-force (* (- 1.0 current-y) 0.15))
             
             ;; Damping
             (damping (* deform-vel -0.1))
             
             ;; Update velocity and scale
             (new-vel (+ deform-vel impact-force spring-force damping))
             (new-y (+ current-y new-vel))
             (new-x (/ 1.0 new-y))
             
             (final-x (+ (entity/get e 'scale-x) (* (- new-x (entity/get e 'scale-x)) 0.3)))
             (final-y (+ current-y (* (- new-y current-y) 0.3))))
        
        (entity/set! e 'deform-vel new-vel)
        (entity/set! e 'scale-x final-x)
        (entity/set! e 'scale-y final-y)))))))
```

The ball now has a *velocity* in the deformation dimension. On impact, it's pushed toward squash; then the spring force pulls it back, causing it to overshoot and briefly stretch before settling.

[VISUAL: A ball that squashes on landing, then stretches tall before settling into its rest shape.]

## Directional Stretch: Following the Velocity Vector

So far, we've only stretched along the vertical axis. A ball moving diagonally should stretch along its direction of travel.

```scheme
;; A ball that stretches along its velocity vector
(let ((ball (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 100 :y 50 :radius 22 :vx 8 :vy 0)))
  (entity/gravity-scale! ball 1.0)
  (entity/bounce! ball 0.7)
  (entity/set! ball 'floor 300)
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! ball 'rotation 0.0)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((vel (entity/vel e))
             (vx (car vel))
             (vy (cdr vel))
             (speed (dsqrt (+ (* vx vx) (* vy vy))))
             (angle (datan2 vy vx))
             
             ;; Stretch along velocity
             (stretch-y (+ 1.0 (* speed 0.008)))
             (stretch-x (/ 1.0 stretch-y))
             
             (current-x (entity/get e 'scale-x))
             (current-y (entity/get e 'scale-y))
             (current-rot (entity/get e 'rotation))
             (ease-rate 0.2)
             (new-x (+ current-x (* (- stretch-x current-x) ease-rate)))
             (new-y (+ current-y (* (- stretch-y current-y) ease-rate)))
             (new-rot (+ current-rot (* (- angle current-rot) ease-rate))))
        
        (entity/set! e 'scale-x new-x)
        (entity/set! e 'scale-y new-y)
        (entity/set! e 'rotation new-rot)))))))
```

The ball rotates to align with its velocity and stretches along that axis. It reads as a projectile.

[VISUAL: A ball traveling in an arc, stretched into an ellipse aligned with its direction of motion.]

## Anticipation: Squash Before Launch

When a character or object is about to jump or launch, it often *squashes down* first — an anticipation that loads energy before the release. This is a timing + deformation composition.

```scheme
;; A ball that squashes before jumping
(let ((ball (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 280 :radius 24 :vy 0)))
  (entity/set! ball 'floor 300)
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! ball 'phase 'anticipate)
  (entity/set! ball 'timer 0)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((phase (entity/get e 'phase))
             (timer (entity/get e 'timer))
             (new-timer (+ timer 1)))
        
        (cond
          ((eq? phase 'anticipate)
           (let* ((progress (/ timer 20.0))
                  (squash (+ 1.0 (* progress -0.5)))
                  (target-y squash)
                  (target-x (/ 1.0 target-y)))
             (entity/set! e 'scale-x target-x)
             (entity/set! e 'scale-y target-y)
             (when (> timer 20)
               (entity/set! e 'phase 'launch)
               (entity/set! e 'timer 0)
               (entity/set-vel! e 0 -15)
               (entity/gravity-scale! e 1.0)
               (entity/bounce! e 0.7))))
          
          ((eq? phase 'launch)
           (let* ((vel-y (cdr (entity/vel e)))
                  (speed (abs vel-y))
                  (target-y (+ 1.0 (* speed 0.01)))
                  (target-x (/ 1.0 target-y))
                  (current-x (entity/get e 'scale-x))
                  (current-y (entity/get e 'scale-y))
                  (ease-rate 0.2)
                  (new-x (+ current-x (* (- target-x current-x) ease-rate)))
                  (new-y (+ current-y (* (- target-y current-y) ease-rate))))
             (entity/set! e 'scale-x new-x)
             (entity/set! e 'scale-y new-y))))
        
        (entity/set! e 'timer new-timer)))))))
```

The ball squashes down over 20 frames, then launches upward with a stretch. The anticipation makes the launch feel powerful.

[VISUAL: A ball that squashes progressively, then rockets upward in a stretched shape.]

## Follow-Through: Trailing Stretch

After a fast motion stops, the trailing edge of the object \"catches up\" — a bit of stretch that lingers and eases out. This is follow-through in the deformation dimension.

```scheme
;; A ball that stretches and lingers after stopping
(let ((ball (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 100 :y 200 :radius 24 :vx 0 :vy 0)))
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! ball 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! ball 'timer 0)
  (entity/set! ball 'phase 'move)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((phase (entity/get e 'phase))
             (timer (entity/get e 'timer))
             (new-timer (+ timer 1)))
        
        (cond
          ((eq? phase 'move)
           (entity/set-vel! e 12 0)
           (let* ((speed 12)
                  (target-y (+ 1.0 (* speed 0.008)))
                  (target-x (/ 1.0 target-y)))
             (entity/set! e 'scale-x target-x)
             (entity/set! e 'scale-y target-y)
             (when (> (entity/x e) 300)
               (entity/set-vel! e 0 0)
               (entity/set! e 'phase 'settle)
               (entity/set! e 'timer 0))))
          
          ((eq? phase 'settle)
           (let* ((current-x (entity/get e 'scale-x))
                  (current-y (entity/get e 'scale-y))
                  (target-x 1.0)
                  (target-y 1.0)
                  (ease-rate 0.05)
                  (new-x (+ current-x (* (- target-x current-x) ease-rate)))
                  (new-y (+ current-y (* (- target-y current-y) ease-rate))))
             (entity/set! e 'scale-x new-x)
             (entity/set! e 'scale-y new-y))))
        
        (entity/set! e 'timer new-timer)))))))
```

The ball races across the screen stretched, then slowly rounds out after stopping. The trailing stretch gives the stop weight.

[VISUAL: A ball that moves fast in a stretched shape, then gradually returns to round after stopping.]

## The Squash-Stretch Cycle: A Heartbeat

An object that pulses — a heart, a jellyfish, a glowing orb — cycles between squash and stretch rhythmically. This is oscillation in the deformation dimension.

```scheme
;; A pulsing heart
(let ((heart (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 200 :radius 30)))
  (entity/set! heart 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! heart 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! heart 'phase 0.0)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((phase (entity/get e 'phase))
             (new-phase (+ phase 0.08))
             (pulse (dsin new-phase))
             (scale (+ 1.0 (* pulse 0.15))))
        (entity/set! e 'scale-x scale)
        (entity/set! e 'scale-y scale)
        (entity/set! e 'phase new-phase)))))))
```

The heart expands and contracts in a sine wave. Uniform scaling gives it a breathing quality.

[VISUAL: A circle that expands and contracts smoothly, like a heartbeat.]

## Asymmetric Pulse: Squash-Then-Stretch

A more complex pulse alternates between squashed-wide and stretched-tall, rather than just growing and shrinking.

```scheme
;; A jellyfish pulse
(let ((jelly (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 200 :radius 35)))
  (entity/set! jelly 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! jelly 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! jelly 'phase 0.0)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((phase (entity/get e 'phase))
             (new-phase (+ phase 0.06))
             (pulse (dsin new-phase))
             (scale-y (+ 1.0 (* pulse 0.25)))
             (scale-x (/ 1.0 scale-y)))
        (entity/set! e 'scale-x scale-x)
        (entity/set! e 'scale-y scale-y)
        (entity/set! e 'phase new-phase)))))))
```

The jellyfish alternates between squashed-wide and stretched-tall, conserving volume. It reads as a soft, rhythmic contraction.

[VISUAL: A circle that alternates between wide-flat and tall-narrow in a smooth cycle.]

## The Blink: A Fast Squash

A blink is a rapid squash-and-recover — often used for eyes, but also for a character reacting to impact or surprise.

```scheme
;; A blinking eye
(let ((eye (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 200 :radius 20)))
  (entity/set! eye 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! eye 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! eye 'timer 0)
  (entity/set! eye 'phase 'open)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((phase (entity/get e 'phase))
             (timer (entity/get e 'timer))
             (new-timer (+ timer 1)))
        
        (cond
          ((eq? phase 'open)
           (entity/set! e 'scale-y 1.0)
           (entity/set! e 'scale-x 1.0)
           (when (> timer 60)
             (entity/set! e 'phase 'closing)
             (entity/set! e 'timer 0)))
          
          ((eq? phase 'closing)
           (let* ((progress (/ timer 3.0))
                  (scale-y (- 1.0 (* progress 0.85))))
             (entity/set! e 'scale-y scale-y)
             (entity/set! e 'scale-x 1.0)
             (when (>= timer 3)
               (entity/set! e 'phase 'opening)
               (entity/set! e 'timer 0))))
          
          ((eq? phase 'opening)
           (let* ((progress (/ timer 6.0))
                  (scale-y (+ 0.15 (* progress 0.85))))
             (entity/set! e 'scale-y scale-y)
             (entity/set! e 'scale-x 1.0)
             (when (>= timer 6)
               (entity/set! e 'phase 'open)
               (entity/set! e 'timer 0)))))
        
        (entity/set! e 'timer new-timer)))))))
```

The eye stays open for 60 frames, squashes rapidly over 3 frames, then opens slowly over 6. The asymmetry gives it a natural blink feel.

[VISUAL: A circle that stays round, rapidly flattens, then slowly returns to round — a blink.]

## Multi-Part Squash: A Character Body

A character with separate body parts — head, torso, legs — can squash each part independently, creating a more complex deformation.

```scheme
;; A character landing with squash distributed across parts
(let ((head (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 150 :radius 16))
      (torso (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 185 :radius 24))
      (legs (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 225 :radius 18)))
  
  (entity/set! head 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! head 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! torso 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! torso 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! legs 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! legs 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! head 'part 'head)
  (entity/set! torso 'part 'torso)
  (entity/set! legs 'part 'legs)
  
  (entity/set! torso 'timer 0)
  (entity/set! torso 'phase 'fall)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (let* ((torso-entity (world/find (lambda (e) (eq? (entity/get e 'part) 'torso))))
           (phase (entity/get torso-entity 'phase))
           (timer (entity/get torso-entity 'timer))
           (new-timer (+ timer 1)))
      
      (cond
        ((eq? phase 'fall)
         (when (> timer 20)
           (entity/set! torso-entity 'phase 'land)
           (entity/set! torso-entity 'timer 0)))
        
        ((eq? phase 'land)
         (world/each (lambda (e)
           (let* ((part (entity/get e 'part))
                  (progress (/ timer 10.0))
                  (squash-head (- 1.0 (* progress 0.15)))
                  (squash-torso (- 1.0 (* progress 0.35)))
                  (squash-legs (- 1.0 (* progress 0.25))))
             
             (cond
               ((eq? part 'head)
                (entity/set! e 'scale-y squash-head)
                (entity/set! e 'scale-x (/ 1.0 squash-head)))
               ((eq? part 'torso)
                (entity/set! e 'scale-y squash-torso)
                (entity/set! e 'scale-x (/ 1.0 squash-torso)))
               ((eq? part 'legs)
                (entity/set! e 'scale-y squash-legs)
                (entity/set! e 'scale-x (/ 1.0 squash-legs))))))
         
         (when (>= timer 10)
           (entity/set! torso-entity 'phase 'recover)
           (entity/set! torso-entity 'timer 0))))
      
      (entity/set! torso-entity 'timer new-timer)))))
```

The legs squash first and most, the torso next, and the head least. The staggered deformation gives the landing a sense of weight traveling through the body.

[VISUAL: Three stacked circles representing a character; on landing, the bottom squashes first and most, then the middle, then the top, each with different amounts.]

## Squash-Stretch Dialogue: Action and Reaction

When two objects collide, they both deform — one squashing, one stretching, depending on their relative masses and velocities.

```scheme
;; Two balls colliding with reciprocal deformation
(let ((ball-a (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 150 :y 200 :radius 24 :vx 6 :vy 0))
      (ball-b (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 350 :y 200 :radius 24 :vx -4 :vy 0)))
  
  (entity/set! ball-a 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! ball-a 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! ball-b 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! ball-b 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! ball-a 'name 'a)
  (entity/set! ball-b 'name 'b)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (let* ((a (world/find (lambda (e) (eq? (entity/get e 'name) 'a))))
           (b (world/find (lambda (e) (eq? (entity/get e 'name) 'b))))
           (dist (entity/distance a b))
           (colliding (< dist 48)))
      
      (if colliding
          (let* ((vel-a (entity/vel a))
                 (vel-b (entity/vel b))
                 (rel-vel (- (car vel-a) (car vel-b)))
                 (impact-force (abs rel-vel))
                 (squash-a (- 1.0 (* impact-force 0.05)))
                 (squash-b (- 1.0 (* impact-force 0.05))))
            (entity/set! a 'scale-x (/ 1.0 squash-a))
            (entity/set! a 'scale-y squash-a)
            (entity/set! b 'scale-x (/ 1.0 squash-b))
            (entity/set! b 'scale-y squash-b)
            (entity/set-vel! a (* (car vel-a) -0.8) 0)
            (entity/set-vel! b (* (car vel-b) -0.8) 0))
          
          (let* ((current-a-x (entity/get a 'scale-x))
                 (current-a-y (entity/get a 'scale-y))
                 (current-b-x (entity/get b 'scale-x))
                 (current-b-y (entity/get b 'scale-y))
                 (ease-rate 0.2)
                 (new-a-x (+ current-a-x (* (- 1.0 current-a-x) ease-rate)))
                 (new-a-y (+ current-a-y (* (- 1.0 current-a-y) ease-rate)))
                 (new-b-x (+ current-b-x (* (- 1.0 current-b-x) ease-rate)))
                 (new-b-y (+ current-b-y (* (- 1.0 current-b-y) ease-rate))))
            (entity/set! a 'scale-x new-a-x)
            (entity/set! a 'scale-y new-a-y)
            (entity/set! b 'scale-x new-b-x)
            (entity/set! b 'scale-y new-b-y)))))))
```

Both balls squash horizontally when they collide, then ease back to round as they bounce apart.

[VISUAL: Two balls approaching each other, squashing horizontally on contact, then separating and rounding out.]

## The Splat: Maximum Squash

A water balloon or egg hitting the ground doesn't bounce — it squashes to nearly nothing, then spreads wide and stays there.

```scheme
;; A water balloon splatting
(let ((balloon (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 50 :radius 26 :vy 0)))
  (entity/gravity-scale! balloon 1.0)
  (entity/set! balloon 'floor 300)
  (entity/set! balloon 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! balloon 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! balloon 'phase 'falling)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((ground 300)
             (dist-to-floor (- ground (entity/y e)))
             (phase (entity/get e 'phase)))
        
        (cond
          ((eq? phase 'falling)
           (when (< dist-to-floor 5)
             (entity/set! e 'phase 'splat)
             (entity/set-vel! e 0 0)))
          
          ((eq? phase 'splat)
           (let* ((current-x (entity/get e 'scale-x))
                  (current-y (entity/get e 'scale-y))
                  (target-y 0.15)
                  (target-x 3.0)
                  (ease-rate 0.15)
                  (new-x (+ current-x (* (- target-x current-x) ease-rate)))
                  (new-y (+ current-y (* (- target-y current-y) ease-rate))))
             (entity/set! e 'scale-x new-x)
             (entity/set! e 'scale-y new-y))))))))))
```

The balloon squashes to a sliver and spreads wide, staying in that splatted state.

[VISUAL: A balloon falling, hitting the ground, and flattening into a wide puddle shape.]

## The Compress-and-Expand: A Spring

A spring compresses when pressed, then expands past its rest length, oscillating before settling.

```scheme
;; A spring compressed and released
(let ((spring (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 200 :radius 20)))
  (entity/set! spring 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! spring 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! spring 'compress-vel 0.0)
  (entity/set! spring 'timer 0)
  (entity/set! spring 'phase 'idle)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((phase (entity/get e 'phase))
             (timer (entity/get e 'timer))
             (new-timer (+ timer 1)))
        
        (cond
          ((eq? phase 'idle)
           (when (> timer 30)
             (entity/set! e 'phase 'compress)
             (entity/set! e 'timer 0)))
          
          ((eq? phase 'compress)
           (let* ((progress (/ timer 10.0))
                  (scale-y (- 1.0 (* progress 0.6))))
             (entity/set! e 'scale-y scale-y)
             (entity/set! e 'scale-x (/ 1.0 scale-y))
             (when (>= timer 10)
               (entity/set! e 'phase 'release)
               (entity/set! e 'compress-vel 0.1)
               (entity/set! e 'timer 0))))
          
          ((eq? phase 'release)
           (let* ((compress-vel (entity/get e 'compress-vel))
                  (current-y (entity/get e 'scale-y))
                  (spring-force (* (- 1.0 current-y) 0.2))
                  (damping (* compress-vel -0.08))
                  (new-vel (+ compress-vel spring-force damping))
                  (new-y (+ current-y new-vel))
                  (new-x (/ 1.0 new-y)))
             (entity/set! e 'compress-vel new-vel)
             (entity/set! e 'scale-y new-y)
             (entity/set! e 'scale-x new-x))))
        
        (entity/set! e 'timer new-timer)))))))
```

The spring compresses over 10 frames, then oscillates before settling back to rest.

[VISUAL: A circle that compresses, then bounces vertically between tall and short before settling.]

## The Inflate: Growing with Air

An object inflating — a balloon, a lung, a bubble — grows with a sense of increasing internal pressure. The deformation accelerates, then slows as it reaches capacity.

```scheme
;; A balloon inflating
(let ((balloon (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 200 :radius 16)))
  (entity/set! balloon 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! balloon 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! balloon 'inflate-vel 0.0)
  (entity/set! balloon 'timer 0)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((timer (entity/get e 'timer))
             (new-timer (+ timer 1))
             (inflate-vel (entity/get e 'inflate-vel))
             (current-scale (entity/get e 'scale-x))
             (max-scale 2.5)
             (inflate-force (if (< current-scale max-scale) 0.015 0.0))
             (drag (* inflate-vel -0.05))
             (new-vel (+ inflate-vel inflate-force drag))
             (new-scale (+ current-scale new-vel)))
        
        (entity/set! e 'inflate-vel new-vel)
        (entity/set! e 'scale-x new-scale)
        (entity/set! e 'scale-y new-scale)
        (entity/set! e 'timer new-timer)))))))
```

The balloon accelerates its growth, then slows as it approaches its maximum size.

[VISUAL: A circle that starts small and grows smoothly, slowing as it reaches its final size.]

## The Pop: Sudden Expansion

When a balloon pops, it doesn't just disappear — it rapidly expands and fades. The deformation is explosive.

```scheme
;; A balloon popping
(let ((balloon (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 200 :radius 20)))
  (entity/set! balloon 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! balloon 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! balloon 'opacity 1.0)
  (entity/set! balloon 'timer 0)
  (entity/set! balloon 'phase 'idle)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((phase (entity/get e 'phase))
             (timer (entity/get e 'timer))
             (new-timer (+ timer 1)))
        
        (cond
          ((eq? phase 'idle)
           (when (> timer 40)
             (entity/set! e 'phase 'pop)
             (entity/set! e 'timer 0)))
          
          ((eq? phase 'pop)
           (let* ((progress (/ timer 8.0))
                  (scale (+ 1.0 (* progress 2.5)))
                  (opacity (- 1.0 (* progress 1.2))))
             (entity/set! e 'scale-x scale)
             (entity/set! e 'scale-y scale)
             (entity/set! e 'opacity opacity)
             (when (>= timer 8)
               (entity/despawn! e)))))
        
        (entity/set! e 'timer new-timer)))))))
```

The balloon rapidly expands while fading, then despawns.

[VISUAL: A circle that suddenly grows large and faint, then disappears.]

## Stretch Leading, Squash Following: The Wave

A wave of deformation can travel along an object — the leading edge stretches, the trailing edge squashes.

```scheme
;; A worm with a traveling wave of squash-stretch
(let ((head (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 150 :y 200 :radius 18))
      (mid (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 200 :radius 18))
      (tail (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 250 :y 200 :radius 18)))
  
  (entity/set! head 'part 'head)
  (entity/set! mid 'part 'mid)
  (entity/set! tail 'part 'tail)
  (entity/set! head 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! head 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! mid 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! mid 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! tail 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! tail 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! head 'phase 0.0)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (let* ((head-entity (world/find (lambda (e) (eq? (entity/get e 'part) 'head))))
           (phase (entity/get head-entity 'phase))
           (new-phase (+ phase 0.15)))
      
      (world/each (lambda (e)
        (let* ((part (entity/get e 'part))
               (offset (cond
                         ((eq? part 'head) 0.0)
                         ((eq? part 'mid) 1.5)
                         ((eq? part 'tail) 3.0)
                         (else 0.0)))
               (local-phase (+ new-phase offset))
               (wave (dsin local-phase))
               (scale-x (+ 1.0 (* wave 0.3)))
               (scale-y (/ 1.0 scale-x)))
          (entity/set! e 'scale-x scale-x)
          (entity/set! e 'scale-y scale-y))))
      
      (entity/set! head-entity 'phase new-phase)))))
```

The deformation wave travels from head to tail, giving the worm a sense of locomotion through squash-stretch undulation.

[VISUAL: Three circles in a row, each squashing and stretching in sequence as a wave travels along them.]

## Recoil: Stretch Before Squash

A punch or strike often *stretches* the arm back before releasing forward. This is the opposite of anticipation — the windup is a stretch, not a squash.

```scheme
;; An arm recoiling before punching
(let ((fist (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 150 :y 200 :radius 18))
      (arm (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 200 :radius 14)))
  
  (entity/set! fist 'part 'fist)
  (entity/set! arm 'part 'arm)
  (entity/set! fist 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! fist 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! arm 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! arm 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! fist 'timer 0)
  (entity/set! fist 'phase 'recoil)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (let* ((fist-entity (world/find (lambda (e) (eq? (entity/get e 'part) 'fist))))
           (phase (entity/get fist-entity 'phase))
           (timer (entity/get fist-entity 'timer))
           (new-timer (+ timer 1)))
      
      (cond
        ((eq? phase 'recoil)
         (let* ((progress (/ timer 15.0))
                (stretch-x (+ 1.0 (* progress 0.4)))
                (stretch-y (/ 1.0 stretch-x)))
           (entity/set! fist-entity 'scale-x stretch-x)
           (entity/set! fist-entity 'scale-y stretch-y)
           (when (>= timer 15)
             (entity/set! fist-entity 'phase 'strike)
             (entity/set! fist-entity 'timer 0))))
        
        ((eq? phase 'strike)
         (let* ((progress (/ timer 5.0))
                (squash-x (- 1.4 (* progress 0.4)))
                (squash-y (/ 1.0 squash-x)))
           (entity/set! fist-entity 'scale-x squash-x)
           (entity/set! fist-entity 'scale-y squash-y)
           (entity/move! fist-entity 15 0)
           (when (>= timer 5)
             (entity/set! fist-entity 'phase 'recover)
             (entity/set! fist-entity 'timer 0))))
        
        ((eq? phase 'recover)
         (let* ((current-x (entity/get fist-entity 'scale-x))
                (current-y (entity/get fist-entity 'scale-y))
                (ease-rate 0.15)
                (new-x (+ current-x (* (- 1.0 current-x) ease-rate)))
                (new-y (+ current-y (* (- 1.0 current-y) ease-rate))))
           (entity/set! fist-entity 'scale-x new-x)
           (entity/set! fist-entity 'scale-y new-y))))
      
      (entity/set! fist-entity 'timer new-timer)))))
```

The fist stretches back, then squashes forward rapidly, then eases back to rest. The stretch-then-squash gives the punch power.

[VISUAL: A circle that stretches horizontally backward, then squashes forward rapidly, then rounds out.]

## The Skid: Horizontal Squash on Sudden Stop

A character sliding to a stop doesn't just halt — the body squashes horizontally from the deceleration, then springs back.

```scheme
;; A character skidding to a stop
(let ((body (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 100 :y 200 :radius 26 :vx 12 :vy 0)))
  (entity/set! body 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! body 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! body 'phase 'slide)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((phase (entity/get e 'phase))
             (vx (car (entity/vel e))))
        
        (cond
          ((eq? phase 'slide)
           (when (> (entity/x e) 300)
             (entity/set-vel! e 0 0)
             (entity/set! e 'phase 'skid)))
          
          ((eq? phase 'skid)
           (let* ((current-x (entity/get e 'scale-x))
                  (current-y (entity/get e 'scale-y))
                  (target-x 0.6)
                  (target-y (/ 1.0 target-x))
                  (ease-rate 0.15)
                  (new-x (+ current-x (* (- target-x current-x) ease-rate)))
                  (new-y (+ current-y (* (- target-y current-y) ease-rate))))
             (entity/set! e 'scale-x new-x)
             (entity/set! e 'scale-y new-y)
             (when (< (abs (- new-x target-x)) 0.05)
               (entity/set! e 'phase 'recover))))
          
          ((eq? phase 'recover)
           (let* ((current-x (entity/get e 'scale-x))
                  (current-y (entity/get e 'scale-y))
                  (ease-rate 0.1)
                  (new-x (+ current-x (* (- 1.0 current-x) ease-rate)))
                  (new-y (+ current-y (* (- 1.0 current-y) ease-rate))))
             (entity/set! e 'scale-x new-x)
             (entity/set! e 'scale-y new-y))))))))))
```

The body squashes horizontally when it stops, then slowly rounds out. It reads as a sudden halt with inertia.

[VISUAL: A circle sliding, stopping abruptly and squashing horizontally, then easing back to round.]

## Breathing: Gentle Expand-Contract

A character at rest breathes — a slow, gentle cycle of expansion and contraction. This is a low-amplitude squash-stretch rhythm.

```scheme
;; A character breathing
(let ((torso (world/spawn :kind 'circle :x 200 :y 200 :radius 30)))
  (entity/set! torso 'scale-x 1.0)
  (entity/set! torso 'scale-y 1.0)
  (entity/set! torso 'breath-phase 0.0)
  
  (world/after 0 (lambda ()
    (world/each (lambda (e)
      (let* ((phase (entity/get e 'breath-phase))
             (new-phase (+ phase 0.04))
             (breath (dsin new-phase))
             (scale (+ 1.0 (* breath 0.08))))
        (entity/set! e 'scale-x scale)
        (entity/set! e 'scale-y scale)
        (entity/set! e 'breath-phase new-phase)))))))
```

The torso expands and contracts gently, giving the character a sense of life.

[VISUAL: A circle that slowly expands and contracts, like a gentle breath.]

## The Trampoline: Double Squash

A character landing on a trampoline squashes the trampoline *and* squashes themselves — two deformations in dialogue.


