## Notes and Additional Considerations from r1 draft

*The following material comes from an earlier or parallel revision draft (r1 draft). It is preserved here because content costs thought — nothing gets thrown away. Some passages restate the chapter's core ideas in a different voice; others introduce examples or angles not covered above. Read as supplemental exercises for the same discipline.*

### First contact: a vertical squash

The simplest case: a circle compressed top-to-bottom, stretched side-to-side to conserve area.

```scheme
(call-with-world
 (make-world width: 400 height: 300 background: '(250 245 235))
 (lambda (w)
   (let ((frame 0))
     (define (draw)
       (world-clear w)
       (let* ((t (/ frame 60.0))
              (squash (+ 0.7 (* 0.3 (sin (* t 3.14))))))
         (world-draw-ellipse w 200 150
                             (* 40 (/ 1.0 (sqrt squash)))
                             (* 40 (sqrt squash))
                             '(220 80 60) 'fill)
         (set! frame (+ frame 1))))
     (world-on-tick w draw 60)
     (world-show w)
     (world-wait w))))
```

[VISUAL: A red ellipse pulsing vertically, staying roughly circular in area.]

The `sqrt` relationship keeps area constant: if height scales by `k`, width scales by `1/sqrt(k)`.

---


### Horizontal squash

Same math, different axis.

```scheme
(call-with-world
 (make-world width: 400 height: 300 background: '(245 250 245))
 (lambda (w)
   (let ((frame 0))
     (define (draw)
       (world-clear w)
       (let* ((t (/ frame 60.0))
              (squash (+ 0.6 (* 0.4 (sin (* t 2.5))))))
         (world-draw-ellipse w 200 150
                             (* 50 (sqrt squash))
                             (* 50 (/ 1.0 (sqrt squash)))
                             '(70 130 180) 'fill)
         (set! frame (+ frame 1))))
     (world-on-tick w draw 60)
     (world-show w)
     (world-wait w))))
```

[VISUAL: A blue ellipse breathing horizontally.]

---


### Bounce anticipation: pre-squash before impact

Before a ball hits the ground, it stretches; at contact, it squashes.

```scheme
(call-with-world
 (make-world width: 400 height: 400 background: '(250 248 240))
 (lambda (w)
   (let ((frame 0))
     (define (draw)
       (world-clear w)
       (let* ((t (modulo (/ frame 90.0) 1.0))
              (y (+ 100 (* 200 t)))
              (stretch (if (< t 0.7) 1.0 (+ 1.0 (* 0.5 (- t 0.7) 3.33))))
              (squash (if (> t 0.9) (- 1.0 (* 0.6 (- t 0.9) 10.0)) 1.0))
              (h-scale (* stretch (/ 1.0 (sqrt squash))))
              (v-scale (* (/ 1.0 stretch) (sqrt squash))))
         (world-draw-ellipse w 200 y
                             (* 35 h-scale)
                             (* 35 v-scale)
                             '(200 90 70) 'fill)
         (set! frame (+ frame 1))))
     (world-on-tick w draw 60)
     (world-show w)
     (world-wait w))))
```

[VISUAL: A falling ball that elongates just before landing, then pancakes at the bottom.]

Stretch kicks in at `t > 0.7`; squash at `t > 0.9`.

---


### Rebound stretch

After squash, the ball springs upward and stretches in the opposite direction.

```scheme
(call-with-world
 (make-world width: 400 height: 400 background: '(245 245 250))
 (lambda (w)
   (let ((frame 0))
     (define (draw)
       (world-clear w)
       (let* ((cycle (modulo (/ frame 80.0) 1.0))
              (y (cond
                  ((< cycle 0.45) (+ 100 (* 180 cycle 2.22)))
                  ((< cycle 0.55) 300)
                  (else (- 300 (* 200 (- cycle 0.55) 2.22)))))
              (v-scale (cond
                        ((< cycle 0.45) 1.0)
                        ((< cycle 0.55) (- 1.0 (* 0.5 (- cycle 0.45) 10.0)))
                        ((< cycle 0.65) (+ 1.0 (* 0.4 (- cycle 0.55) 10.0)))
                        (else 1.0)))
              (h-scale (/ 1.0 (sqrt v-scale))))
         (world-draw-ellipse w 200 y
                             (* 40 h-scale)
                             (* 40 v-scale)
                             '(100 160 100) 'fill)
         (set! frame (+ frame 1))))
     (world-on-tick w draw 60)
     (world-show w)
     (world-wait w))))
```

[VISUAL: A green ball dropping, squashing at the floor, then stretching vertically as it rebounds.]

---


### Asymmetric squash: leaning under load

A shape compressed at an angle, not purely vertical.

```scheme
(call-with-world
 (make-world width: 400 height: 300 background: '(250 250 245))
 (lambda (w)
   (let ((frame 0))
     (define (draw)
       (world-clear w)
       (let* ((t (/ frame 60.0))
              (lean (sin (* t 2.0)))
              (squash (+ 0.7 (* 0.2 (abs lean))))
